  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 46.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he bought a linen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "cloth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σινδόνα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This was a fine linen garment, or shroud, something like that in which the young man fled the night before (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:51, 52",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And taking him down",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "καθελὼν αὐτὸν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It appears from these words that Joseph himself, assisted probably by Nicodemus and others, actually took the body of our Lord down from the cross. wrapped the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "sindon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " round him, and laid him in his own new tomb, which had been hewn out of the rock. The word rendered \"tomb\" is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μνημεῖον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as being intended to be a memorial of the departed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he rolled a stone against the door of the tomb.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The door here means \"the opening,\" or \"entrance.\" Thus, while our Lord died with the wicked, he was with the rich in his death (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 53:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Mark 15:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
